unit.name: LVIII Panzer Korps HQ
unit.History: LVIII Panzerkorps was formed in July 1944 as the "Reserve LVIII Panzerkorps". On July 6th, 1944 it was renamed "LVIII Panzerkorps". It operated in France, and later in the Ardennes, as part of the 5th Panzer Army.

commander.Name: Walter Krueger
commander.PersBio: Before the outbreak of World War 2, Walter Krueger commanded the 10th Cavalry Regiment. When Germany mobilized, this regiment was disbanded, and Krueger took over the 171st Infantry Regiment. In October 1939 he became chief of staff of the 1st Rifle Brigade of the 1st Panzer Division, taking over command of the brigade in February 1940. After winning the Knight's Cross and a promotion to Major-General, he became commander of the 1st Panzer Division in July 1941. He commanded this division in Russia, France and Greece before before becoming commander of the LVIII Pz Korps on January 1st, 1944.
commander.Title: CO

estab.Name: WF - HR - Panzer Corps Tac HQ

unit.name: 116 Panzer Div HQ
unit.History: This Westphalian unit was formed in March 1944 from the 16th Panzergrenadier Division. The division was nicknamed ‘Windhund’ (Greyhound) division, after its divisional insignia. The 16th Panzergrenadier Division had fought on the southern sector of the Russian front, but the 116th Panzer only saw action in the West, fighting in Normandy, around Aachen and in the Huertgen Forest. For Operation “Wacht am Rhein” the 116th was assigned to the 5th Panzer Army.

commander.Name: Siegfried von Waldenburg
commander.PersBio: A veteran of WW I, Waldenburg served in various staff functions before taking command of the 26th Panzergrenadier Regiment. He then commanded the 25th Panzergrenadier Divison, and in September 1944 he took over the 116th. Waldenburg led from the front, and earned the Knights Cross.

unit.name: 560 Volksgrenadier Div HQ
unit.History: The division was formed in August 1944 in Norway as the 560th Grenadier Division, and was quickly renamed 560th Volksgrenadier Division. It was only posted to the western front just before the start of Operation “Wacht am Rhein”, so it had no combat experience when the offensive started.

commander.Name: Rudolf Langhaeuser
commander.PersBio: Langhaeuser was acting commander of the division while its commander, Major-General Rudolf Bader, was in hospital.

unit.name: Führer-Begleit-Brigade HQ
unit.History: Originating from the Führer-Begleit-Regiment 'GD', the Führer-Begleit-Brigade was formed in September 1944 at the Wolfsschanze in Rastenburg. Its original mission was to protect the HQ and its surrounding area against suspected Allied air landings. In Late November, the unit was transferred to the West and further expanded for committal in the Ardennes Offensive. According to Otto Remer, the Brigade's CO, the HQ of the former Führer-Begleit-Regiment acted as the HQ for the entire Brigade. Also, an assigned Panzer-Regimental HQ arrived too late and too disorganised to be committed. As a consequence, the Brigade's HQ had a very heavy command burden, with II./Pz.Rgt. 'GD', StuG-Brig. 200, Gren.Btl. 928 zbV, II./Lehr-Art.Abt. 5 and the Führer-Flak-Rgt. under its command, next to its original two battalions. After the Ardennes Offensive the Brigade was further expanded into a division.

commander.Name: Ernst Otto Remer
commander.PersBio: After serving on both the Eastern and Western Front, Remer commanded the "Wachregiment Grossdeutschland" in Berlin in July 1944. In this capacity, he was crucial in stopping the insurgents plot of July 20. As a reward, Remer was given command of the newly created Führer Begleit Brigade, which saw its first action in East Prussia. It turned out that Remer was not particularly suited for higher command, but his high standing with the top of the Nazi hierarchy prevented his replacement. During the Battle of the Bulge Remer again commanded his brigade with little distinction.
commander.Title: CO

unit.name: Pz Bn FBB HQ
unit.History: This was the former II. /Pz.Regt. 'Grossdeutschland', which was transferred to the Führer-Begleit-Brigade to act as its I. Panzer-Abteilung. It was equipped with Pz IV / 70 (A), which was in fact a tank destroyer. Attached as its 4th Coy was the former 5. Pz.Kp. / Führer-Begleit-Regiment, which had a mixed equipment of Pz IV J and StuG III.
